So you can raise your hand on Zoom, and I'll keep an eye out.

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:56.720
You can put questions in the Zoom chat, and feel free to just put a little star next to

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.400
it if it's something you want me to read instead.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:05.480
And then we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:09.479
And Caitlin, if you don't mind sharing that in the chat right now that oh, Hannah got

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:10.479
it already.

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:11.479
Awesome.

00:02:11.479 --> 00:02:12.479
Thank you.

00:02:12.479 --> 00:02:15.600
But you can ask questions anonymously there as well.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:18.639
But with all that, thanks again so much for joining us.

00:02:18.639 --> 00:02:24.720
I am so excited to be joined by my co-host today, Colonel Chris Saling, Director of Innovation

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:29.039
at U.S. Army Human Resources Command.

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:33.080
And Chris, I'd love to kick things off with maybe having you introduce yourself and sharing

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:38.320
a little bit about your role today, and something you like to do outside of work too.

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:42.320
No, that sounds good, and thank you so much for that, Rachel.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.639
So as you said, I'm the Director of Innovation for U.S. Army Human Resources Command, and

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:48.839
everybody always tries to figure out what that is.

00:02:48.839 --> 00:02:50.880
Innovation has become a buzzword.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:53.880
We always talk about innovation theater and everything else.

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:58.119
Our job is to be a little bit of a future concept cell for the commanding general so

00:02:58.119 --> 00:03:03.639
that we can be a little bit more removed from the daily asks and asks and figure out how

00:03:03.639 --> 00:03:08.979
we're going to take and update and sometimes transform our processes to get after those

00:03:08.979 --> 00:03:09.979
future concepts.

00:03:09.979 --> 00:03:12.759
So I have a team that is predominantly technologists.

00:03:12.759 --> 00:03:14.360
I have a lot of data scientists.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:15.360
I have a cyber guy.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:16.800
I have a networks guy.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:22.679
I have a human resources digital transformation subject matter expert and a recruiting team.

00:03:22.679 --> 00:03:24.399
And that's just the start of us.

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:28.800
We're a year old, and I think we're going to expand by another 10 positions or so this

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:29.800
coming year.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:30.800
That's great.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:31.800
Thank you.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.919
And outside of work, what's something you like to do?

00:03:34.919 --> 00:03:36.720
I like to cook.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:37.720
So to me, that's my zen.

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:41.440
I'll put on some music, and I'll go in the kitchen and cook something.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:42.440
Nice.

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:45.720
So I know you said this is a new team here.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:51.759
Can you share a little bit about how the creation of that team came to be and maybe how you

00:03:51.759 --> 00:03:54.600
work with some other departments across the Army too?

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:55.600
Yeah.

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:01.000
No, it really kind of started when I was working in, just for some context, I've been working

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.039
out of the Army people space for seven going on eight years now, which is kind of atypical.

00:04:06.039 --> 00:04:10.639
But a lot of what we've been doing is digital modernization and transformation.

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:15.080
The Army came out with the Army People Strategy, I want to say, in 2019 or early 2020, that

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:20.119
talked about how we wanted to modernize how we did talent management, pushed a lot, did

00:04:20.119 --> 00:04:23.959
a lot of different pilots and prototypes, got a bunch of policies changed.

00:04:23.959 --> 00:04:28.239
We did some great stuff there and then realized that we hadn't modernized the mechanisms to

00:04:28.239 --> 00:04:30.279
actually get us to talent management.

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:35.839
We were still basically assigning people and moving people around using the same old systems,

00:04:35.839 --> 00:04:39.660
and a lot of them really needed to be updated.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:46.059
So we needed a way to look out and see how we could do that cohesively rather than just

00:04:46.059 --> 00:04:49.480
looking at the individual processes of the directorates.

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:53.779
So General Drew made the decision that he was going to establish the innovation cell

00:04:53.779 --> 00:05:00.640
to solidify our HRC 2030 vision that we have, and to look at how we're going to step forward

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.980
in our technology and our business practices to achieve it.

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:04.980
I see.

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:08.519
Katherine, you had a question in the chat, do you want to jump in here first?

00:05:08.519 --> 00:05:13.140
It was really just a question on whether or not all of the people on your team are

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:17.799
in active duty in the military, or if some of those are also GS positions, or what your

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:19.359
team makeup looks like.

00:05:19.359 --> 00:05:21.399
Yeah, it's military and civilian.

00:05:21.399 --> 00:05:26.160
Right now, we're mostly military just because I took my team, I realigned my team that I

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:29.880
have for talent management with me, but we've made a couple civilian hires and we're going

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:33.959
to make a number of other civilian hires.

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:41.640
So a question I had wanted to ask you about is, Caitlin and I were talking about how you've

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.239
managed to kind of break silos between the different army departments and getting people

00:05:46.239 --> 00:05:51.640
to work together to help achieve the team's vision.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:54.880
And I was just wondering, like, how have you been able to do that?

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:59.880
And what tips do you have for some of us who are maybe trying to do the same thing and

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.959
break silos within our own organizations?

00:06:02.959 --> 00:06:08.200
Yeah, I mean, one of the biggest skills that we, we harp a lot on command in the military,

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:10.079
but that's not the most important leadership skill.

00:06:10.079 --> 00:06:13.799
One of the most important things that we consider is building coalitions, you know, how do you

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:18.880
reach out to your counterparts and get a whole bunch of people crashing together on a common

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:20.720
goal or a common understanding?

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:24.679
I think one of the places we've had the biggest success with that is with our data literacy

00:06:24.679 --> 00:06:25.679
program.

00:06:25.679 --> 00:06:30.480
As we had a lot of people with needs, we had a lot of people who are looking for more data,

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:36.079
and we were able to pull people from throughout the army to look at this as a project and

00:06:36.079 --> 00:06:37.079
get it scaled up.

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:38.959
So now it's part of our professional military education.

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:39.959
Thank you.

00:06:39.959 --> 00:06:43.359
I think Mike's question there kind of touches on this as well.

00:06:43.359 --> 00:06:45.320
Mike, do you want to expand on that?

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:50.519
Yeah, and actually, I think you answered part of it, but, you know, you're, you're, as you're

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:54.160
building your team, and this is a kind of question that we hear a lot at Data Science

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:58.480
Hangout, did those team members already have data science skills, or are they having to

00:06:58.480 --> 00:06:59.480
learn as they go?

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:01.720
So I had a mix.

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:05.359
One I hired straight out of grad school out of the Georgetown Data Science Program.

00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:09.519
Another I hired from Notre Dame, the Computer Science Program.

00:07:09.519 --> 00:07:13.839
So they had a number of different data skills, they had to, you know, kind of cross train

00:07:13.839 --> 00:07:15.799
into other areas of emphasis.

00:07:15.799 --> 00:07:20.839
Obviously, natural language processing and texturing analysis is big when you're in the

00:07:20.839 --> 00:07:23.380
people space.

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:26.399
One of them came in with a lot of those skills, the others are having to learn it.

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:31.880
And then I have a couple other folks who were very good statistical analysts, didn't

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:36.160
have the same kind of experience in building out some of the applications we were building.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:42.000
So we're using a number of different kind of training programs, upscaling, pair coding,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.279
to try to get them set on that.

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:50.839
Then I do have some folks who come in straight from the HR side, very limited exposure to

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:51.839
data and data science.

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:55.600
And it gave me an opportunity to kind of test our data literacy training on them to get

00:07:55.799 --> 00:07:58.559
them to ask more, you know, intelligent data questions.

00:07:58.559 --> 00:08:03.119
Not that they weren't asking intelligent questions, but there's less translation needed between

00:08:03.119 --> 00:08:06.160
them and our data folks.

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:10.040
I'm sure I'll follow up questions in a minute, but I'll come back to you.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:12.559
Patrick, I see you just put a question in the chat.

00:08:12.559 --> 00:08:13.559
Want to jump in here?

00:08:13.559 --> 00:08:14.559
Yeah, thank you, Rachel.

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:16.839
It's sort of a follow up to what you just said, Kirsten.

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:17.839
Thank you for being here.

00:08:17.839 --> 00:08:19.239
I'm fascinated by this.

00:08:19.239 --> 00:08:21.359
You mentioned text analysis and NLP.

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:25.920
What are your key data sources for bringing that in to the analytic pipeline and then

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:30.119
also other data sources, more quantitatively focused stuff?

00:08:30.119 --> 00:08:35.400
So we use a number of different kind of commercial products.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.400
We'll use Hugging Face.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:40.719
We'll use a number of other things you guys are probably familiar with to help us at least

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:42.080
kind of break down our taxonomies.

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:45.960
But most of the work that we're doing comes from our evaluation entry system, where we

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.520
are looking at evaluations.

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.520
We're looking at duty descriptions.

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:58.760
We're looking at how we establish our taxonomies and ontologies for job competencies.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:02.280
There are a lot of libraries out there that we could build, but there's not really a spacey

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:06.320
library out there for military competency.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:09.039
So we've had to build, practically build our own.

00:09:09.039 --> 00:09:12.080
Does that kind of answer your question?

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:13.080
Yeah, thank you.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:14.559
My answer was all over the place.

00:09:14.559 --> 00:09:16.119
No, that's awesome.

00:09:16.119 --> 00:09:18.280
And it's wonderful work you all are doing.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:19.280
So thank you very much.

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:20.280
No, thank you.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:24.919
I'm going to go back to the conversation about breaking down silos a bit.

00:09:24.919 --> 00:09:30.679
Luke had asked in the chat, in such a gigantic operation, how have you been able to actually

00:09:30.679 --> 00:09:34.299
break down those data silos to get what you need?

00:09:34.299 --> 00:09:38.359
So the first step we had to do was convince senior leaders to be directive.

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:42.080
I mean, it's horrible to say, you think we're going to want to cooperate and share, but

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:45.280
nobody wants to cooperate and share their data.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:49.640
So we went to the Secretary of the Army and said, I have a directive here that says all

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:53.640
the people in the people space will share their people data, period.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:57.440
So it was our first people analytics core directive.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:02.479
We've refreshed that a couple of times, and we've identified our person event data environment

00:10:02.479 --> 00:10:06.440
as kind of being the semi-official repository for that data sharing.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:09.200
We get a lot of people who are working in that environment.

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:11.919
It's probably something a lot of you will be familiar with.

00:10:11.919 --> 00:10:17.359
It's just a massive data warehouse with a virtual machine environment on top of it that

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:23.320
we use to drop different data sets in to do different projects.

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:27.080
But yeah, no, we had to basically order everybody to share their data.

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:31.200
I'm trying to think how that might translate to some of these students here too.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:32.200
Yeah.

00:10:32.200 --> 00:10:35.280
Well, it's like, I mean, I think the biggest piece, we talked about building coalitions.

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:41.200
You know, there's going to be, we tried to do some data summits across the Army just

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:44.039
to bring people together and talk about what they were working on.

00:10:44.039 --> 00:10:46.799
And man, it would be really cool if we could just get our hands on, well, there's probably

00:10:46.799 --> 00:10:49.520
somebody in the room who knows how to get their hands on that data.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:54.320
So we started this little bit of a coalition talking about, wouldn't it be great if we

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:55.320
could do all this?

00:10:55.320 --> 00:11:00.200
And that's how we pitched the argument to leadership to say, look, we've got to, we've

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:01.200
got to get here.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.200
We've got to be able to do this.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:04.320
And we need your support and endorsement.

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:05.320
Ours was very directive.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:10.080
But I think if you have a leader there who does give you that champion, that support

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:13.159
and endorsement, that might be a good corollary.

00:11:13.159 --> 00:11:14.159
Definitely.

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:17.479
Colter, I see you had a question in the chat.

00:11:17.479 --> 00:11:18.479
Want to jump in here next?

00:11:18.479 --> 00:11:19.479
Sure.

00:11:19.479 --> 00:11:20.479
Yeah.

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:21.479
And you actually just kind of answered it.

00:11:21.479 --> 00:11:26.280
But I was wondering if, from your perspective, if you've seen similar data modernization

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:32.099
efforts happening, either within other commands, I'm thinking of like a futures command or

00:11:32.099 --> 00:11:36.880
even within kind of individual branches within the Army, if there are similar efforts going

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:37.880
on.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:38.880
Oh yeah.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:46.719
So we've really got a, just, it warms my heart, data modernization trends.

00:11:46.719 --> 00:11:48.320
Army Futures Command is a big partner.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:52.539
Their data science division, Nate Parker over there is a big partner of ours in looking

00:11:52.539 --> 00:11:54.359
at how we can get more agile data science.

00:11:54.359 --> 00:11:59.679
I mean, I hate to say agile, not in terms of agile development, but something that'll

00:11:59.679 --> 00:12:04.919
flex better into our different requirements.

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:08.840
So we're working with him and seeing if we can use that instead of our current environment.

00:12:09.799 --> 00:12:12.799
We've reached out to 18th Airborne Corps who is using our Vantage program, which is built

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:21.159
on Palantir Foundry to do a lot of their work, a lot of their data work, informing decisions.

00:12:21.159 --> 00:12:27.599
We've worked with the Army AI Integration Center that is now up at Carnegie Mellon.

00:12:27.599 --> 00:12:29.440
We've had a lot of great partners in the West Point.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:30.440
I can't leave out West Point.

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:36.960
Partner and good friend, Colonel Nick Clark, who started our data literacy training program

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:41.200
that we've kind of incorporated and taken Army-wide.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:45.599
But yeah, and I think kind of coming back to finding those partners in the coalition,

00:12:45.599 --> 00:12:49.200
as we figured out who all is working in this space, we've been able to kind of give each

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:53.280
other a hand up when people need resources or endorsement, and it's really made things

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:54.280
spread faster.

00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:59.400
I know we touched on the data literacy program a few times, and I was just curious, like,

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:02.799
what does that program look like?

00:13:02.799 --> 00:13:08.080
So the initial iteration was just 10 hours of coursework, basically making people better

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:09.559
critical consumers of data.

00:13:09.559 --> 00:13:11.359
Oh, hey, Nate's here.

00:13:11.359 --> 00:13:14.760
Yes, you've always got to give a shout out.

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:16.760
Making people better critical consumers of data.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:21.400
That's expanded to about a 16-hour course that's going to be in kind of our basic professional

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:23.080
military education.

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:26.400
There's a second level that they're going to get in that next iteration, which is more

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:30.039
hands-on, using the common tools that you have available.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:36.000
We'll start folks out just doing basic statistical analysis in Excel or whatever they have access

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:37.000
to.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.320
We want to start introducing them into R and Python so that it's not scary.

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:43.960
We can learn how to code, share some of those resources.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:48.919
So if they're interested or if their branch has opportunities, they go into level three,

00:13:48.919 --> 00:13:52.840
which is where we take them into some in-depth analytic training.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:58.880
That walks them through our data competency model, and we basically create learning paths

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:02.760
for all the different things that they want to do, if they want to get into different

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.159
types of coding, if they want to do more NLP.

00:14:05.159 --> 00:14:07.159
I need more NLP programmers.

00:14:07.159 --> 00:14:12.960
Yeah, that's always the fun part too, when you talk about NLP with a bunch of data scientists.

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:18.080
You know who your natural language processors are, and then you know who your optimizers

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:22.919
are because they're like, wait, what are you talking about melding your programs for?

00:14:22.919 --> 00:14:29.599
That actually leads me to a question that was asked anonymously was, how much is R or

00:14:29.599 --> 00:14:32.840
Python used in your organization?

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:39.640
So a majority of our folks are Python users just because of our Vantage program being

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:43.840
built on Foundry, which is PyJR and PySpark.

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:49.400
I've got a couple of folks who do use R fairly regularly doing their analysis.

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:55.919
We had a lot of people on kind of the more legacy programs, looking at SPSS and SAS,

00:14:55.919 --> 00:14:58.159
not to disparage those, but they're expensive.

00:14:58.159 --> 00:15:01.559
So we want people getting on things where they can more rapidly develop and share.

00:15:01.559 --> 00:15:07.239
Like my team, we try to use as much of the existing language and share code as much as

00:15:07.239 --> 00:15:09.719
possible, but it gets difficult.

