Well, one of the programs that we're working on is just a big neural net that takes in

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:10.599
all our personnel data and rolls out a prediction vector of how likely someone is to retreat

00:27:10.599 --> 00:27:12.599
from service over time.

00:27:12.599 --> 00:27:17.880
So we do a lot of retention analysis.

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:23.619
We're trying to figure out how to improve on an existing simulation that shows how our

00:27:23.619 --> 00:27:26.719
distribution could get backed up.

00:27:26.719 --> 00:27:33.000
We want to try to forecast what our force is going to look like, our force inventory

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:36.800
is going to look like over five years, because obviously, you probably heard in the news

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:39.719
about the recruiting issues.

00:27:39.719 --> 00:27:44.280
Issues sounds too kind, but I'm on camera, so I'll just say recruiting issues.

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:48.680
But that's going to leave a little bit of a trough in the force, even if we recover

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:54.079
from it in the very near future, it's still going to be something that we have to build

00:27:54.079 --> 00:27:57.680
our inventory around over the next five, 10 years.

00:27:57.680 --> 00:28:03.880
So we want to be able to take a look at what that looks like and prioritize skill development

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:06.199
and assignments accordingly.

00:28:06.199 --> 00:28:08.959
So we're trying to build some of those forecasting models.

