00:29:34.119 --> 00:29:38.520
mismatch program because we were trying to figure out with all the rapid changes for our

00:29:38.520 --> 00:29:44.400
new structure, why did we have a force that looked very different from the structure that

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:45.079
we required?

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:48.680
And the answer was, obviously, the senior leaders can say, I want to build this type of

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:52.839
organization. The requirements are built, and it takes much longer for the supply to catch

00:29:52.839 --> 00:29:58.680
up. So as an argument for data-driven talent management, where we look at attribute-based

00:29:58.680 --> 00:30:06.680
assignment versus branch and a grade, like, look how much we can reduce the gap in what we

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.839
have versus what we assign, because we have these skills here.

00:30:08.839 --> 00:30:11.560
They're just coded under another specialty.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:16.560
If we make some of these positions more immaterial, then we have a lot more assignment

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:19.479
options and the ability to fill that talent requirement.

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:22.359
So that one was fairly easy.

00:30:22.359 --> 00:30:25.160
We did it with existing data, existing position analysis.

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:30.439
We have much more in-depth understanding of the requirements now, but we were able to show

00:30:30.439 --> 00:30:34.800
very quickly, it's like, OK, all of these stationing issues that we thought initially were

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:36.680
a problem, much less of a problem.

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:38.079
It's a great example.

00:30:38.079 --> 00:30:38.880
Thank you, Chris.

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:39.920
Thank you.

00:30:40.479 --> 00:30:41.319
And thank you.

00:30:41.319 --> 00:30:47.640
And I echo Arian's comment, love the idea of quick wins projects and kind of spending some

00:30:47.640 --> 00:30:51.719
time thinking about what those could be in our own organizations, too.

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:54.319
Brad, I see you have your hand raised here.

00:30:54.319 --> 00:30:55.000
Do you want to jump in?

00:30:55.959 --> 00:30:56.479
Sure.

00:30:56.959 --> 00:31:02.560
A lot of focus is being paid to AI and machine learning and data mesh and data fabric.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:07.800
And those are, I feel like, advanced concepts, XYZ and the alphabet.

00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:11.400
And if you don't do the ABCs, the XYZs aren't going to turn out very well.

00:31:12.079 --> 00:31:18.959
Do you guys currently have a platform around either data catalog or governance that helps

00:31:19.319 --> 00:31:23.760
people find the right data at the right time and the right reason and use it appropriately?

00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:27.040
So we've rolled one out.

00:31:27.079 --> 00:31:29.119
It doesn't have the kind of use that I would like it to have.

00:31:29.119 --> 00:31:34.760
It's the enterprise EDSC, enterprise data system catalog.

00:31:35.319 --> 00:31:40.119
So it should have everything registered in it that we have and that we're collecting.

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:45.400
And if we could get more people accessing it, I think that would go toward a lot of our

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:45.839
problems.

00:31:45.880 --> 00:31:50.760
The hard part is we're not using the tool directly in with the data systems where that

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:51.520
data is stored.

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:53.160
So we have to manually update it.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:55.920
But it's something that we've considered.

00:31:55.920 --> 00:31:57.119
We've identified that as a need.

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:03.439
And having it, one of the things I'm looking for is a more intelligent data catalog that we

00:32:03.439 --> 00:32:04.000
could roll out.

00:32:04.359 --> 00:32:09.079
I think this question kind of touches upon this as well, that George asked what systems

00:32:09.079 --> 00:32:11.040
are using to share data with people?

00:32:11.479 --> 00:32:13.560
Is that a different use than what we're talking about now?

00:32:14.079 --> 00:32:16.839
So a lot of it is no point to point transfer.

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:23.079
We do just extract transfer load and we've got a number of our systems talking to each

00:32:23.079 --> 00:32:23.959
other through APIs.

00:32:24.479 --> 00:32:30.040
But otherwise, we just have to figure out all kinds of different ways to get the data

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:32.119
sent to the data science environment that we're using.

00:32:32.760 --> 00:32:33.760
It's not always easy.

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:36.479
I mean, we were at the point where they were emailing or they're not emailing, but where

00:32:36.479 --> 00:32:37.959
they were physically mailing hard drives.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:40.680
So we're trying to get away from that, obviously.

00:32:40.839 --> 00:32:41.359
Yeah.

00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:48.880
An anonymous question, interesting question on Slido is how does your team build their own

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:52.800
professional portfolios for when they may move on to a new job?

00:32:53.079 --> 00:32:56.400
Is how can they show what they've done without sharing protected info?

00:32:57.520 --> 00:32:59.280
Yeah, we've we've talked about that a lot.

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:05.079
And the way I've kind of treated the work my team does and because I've been in the

00:33:05.079 --> 00:33:09.280
position and even though this is a new team, a lot of the team I'm working with was one

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:12.520
I worked with for three and a half years in Army Talent Management with Army People

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:18.239
Analytics. And then a couple of years prior to that in G1, I treat all my new hires like

00:33:20.959 --> 00:33:23.640
like they're grad students coming in and they're going to come, they're going to

00:33:23.640 --> 00:33:26.719
explore the data, they're going to get familiar with the data sets we use, get familiar

00:33:26.719 --> 00:33:31.640
with the business processes, and then they kind of will find something that works as a

00:33:31.640 --> 00:33:32.680
thesis project.

00:33:33.520 --> 00:33:35.959
So like what is the thing that grabs them?

00:33:35.959 --> 00:33:37.479
What is the thing that's the most interesting?

00:33:37.479 --> 00:33:39.359
What's most suited to their capabilities?

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:43.400
And we've really kind of built things around that.

00:33:44.719 --> 00:33:51.760
We've been lucky in that there's been so much to do that we could align people to the

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:53.280
projects that they are most interested in.

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:57.040
The thing that we're trying to work out is, you know, what happens if we have projects that are

00:33:57.040 --> 00:33:59.640
prioritized that don't have the same grab?

00:34:01.160 --> 00:34:02.479
But that's kind of how I have it.

00:34:02.479 --> 00:34:04.839
I have this whole laundry list of things that I want to get after.

00:34:04.839 --> 00:34:09.159
And I kind of like, you know, your grad advisor did with their research projects and like,

00:34:09.159 --> 00:34:12.600
hey, let me point you in this direction, go research this a little bit, develop this

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:15.080
program or this problem a little bit more.

00:34:15.080 --> 00:34:16.080
Let's see if that grabs you.

00:34:16.479 --> 00:34:18.560
Yeah, that's an interesting idea.

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:23.719
Yeah, that's an interesting idea, like the thesis project for new people coming in.

00:34:23.719 --> 00:34:30.399
And I see there's a conversation kind of happening in the chat as well about like, well,

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:33.000
adding on to that idea of quick wins.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.199
And then, Alan, I saw you mentioned something about how you do onboarding where people can

00:34:37.199 --> 00:34:38.199
contribute right away.

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:40.840
Would you want to jump in here and share that?

00:34:42.600 --> 00:34:45.360
Sure, I don't think I don't have a ton to add.

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:50.399
We just really try conscientiously to think about as someone's coming onto the team or

00:34:50.399 --> 00:34:54.199
someone's joining the organization, how do we set them up so that they have something

00:34:54.479 --> 00:34:59.399
meaningful to contribute as soon as possible so they don't feel like they're waiting to

00:34:59.399 --> 00:35:03.320
like become credible for a year before people feel like they can contribute?

00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:08.679
And so it's just really important to give people ways to feel successful soon.

00:35:09.360 --> 00:35:14.000
And Chris, I was also reacting to that sort of incoming grad student kind of approach.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:18.159
I think that's such an interesting model to to set that up to say, like, explore this,

00:35:18.159 --> 00:35:20.040
find something interesting, dig into it.

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:22.040
We'll see if we can make a project out of it.

00:35:22.439 --> 00:35:23.439
It's really cool.

00:35:23.439 --> 00:35:28.320
And I also appreciate the dilemma of like, OK, we have to prioritize that against the

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:29.639
portfolio as well.

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:34.280
Now, I like the idea of incorporating the quick wins, too, because that's basically the

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:37.000
kind of stuff we have that new people could get after.

00:35:37.439 --> 00:35:42.679
Like this is this one is I hate using the term low hanging fruit, but this one's kind of

00:35:42.679 --> 00:35:43.840
primed, ready to go.

00:35:44.199 --> 00:35:47.600
Jump on this, chew on it, use it to get familiar with the data.

00:35:48.080 --> 00:35:50.199
And then we kind of go and develop from there.

00:35:50.639 --> 00:35:53.080
OK, I might need help with this acronym.

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:59.159
Maybe a Slido question is how have you navigated OPM requirements as you seek to

00:35:59.159 --> 00:36:02.600
modernize recruitment and retainment, retainment strategies?

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:04.800
Yeah, office personnel management.

00:36:04.800 --> 00:36:10.239
So we really just had to get into the same way we did the military side, the letter of

00:36:10.239 --> 00:36:15.199
the law. It's like, what are these things actually say that we must do and what is

00:36:15.199 --> 00:36:19.959
written in DOD or army policy or something that's just more of like a legacy?

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.199
Like we really try to go back to some of these things and talk about what the ground

00:36:24.199 --> 00:36:31.719
truth is. We haven't really had much of an issue modernizing, at least on the data

00:36:31.719 --> 00:36:34.760
side, because of all the direct hire authorities that we have.

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:42.600
We've really tried to push also towards doing more return hires, which scares people in

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:44.639
government. They're like, oh, you mean they're not going to make this a career?

00:36:45.199 --> 00:36:49.280
People are working in the space, don't want to spend a lifetime in the same job anyway.

00:36:49.639 --> 00:36:51.760
You know, they're going to come in, they're going to do a thing, they're going to pick a

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:58.800
next thing. And you can see if that piece is, you know, that particular position is

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:01.479
validated at the same level because the projects mature.

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:07.399
You might need some entry level folks or you might need some folks to do data

00:37:07.399 --> 00:37:08.719
development, data cleaning.

00:37:08.959 --> 00:37:11.800
And then after that, you'll realize you've got a different use for that data, different

00:37:11.800 --> 00:37:14.040
project, the composition of your project team is going to change.

00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:22.159
So we've really tried to use the most flexible processes we have within the existing

00:37:22.159 --> 00:37:25.919
policies. But we're not afraid to kind of go up to OSD and say, hey, guys, we might want to

00:37:25.919 --> 00:37:27.080
rewrite this thing a little bit.

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:28.600
Look at what we could do if you rewrite it.

00:37:29.199 --> 00:37:30.159
Here's our proposed language.

00:37:30.159 --> 00:37:39.800
Just fine. I noticed in your your bio, you talk about your team conducting research and

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:42.479
doing experiments, the prototype as well.

00:37:43.080 --> 00:37:49.199
And I was wondering, how do you create that culture where it's OK to do these

00:37:49.199 --> 00:37:53.439
experiments? And I'd love to hear a little bit about that.

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:57.080
Getting your bio, like let's not throw a bunch of money at this.

00:37:57.080 --> 00:37:59.439
Let's try it first. I can try it for you for free.

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:02.080
And you can figure out how much money you want to spend on the result.

00:38:02.439 --> 00:38:06.439
I mean, some of them are looking at different data integration in the selection boards.

00:38:07.919 --> 00:38:12.879
As we are doing that, we just have the board members stay on a couple of extra days, do a

00:38:12.879 --> 00:38:16.600
quick rundown with them and pilot some of the new look and feel of the board and see how

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:20.399
much it changes their voting from the previous version.

00:38:20.639 --> 00:38:24.639
And we are looking at things like voter inter-reliability.

00:38:24.719 --> 00:38:28.000
We're able to explore things that we haven't been able to explore before.

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:32.320
And then we bring the findings back again, kind of looking at the quick wins.

00:38:32.320 --> 00:38:35.679
We find the things that are legit findings, bring those back to senior leaders and go,

00:38:35.679 --> 00:38:37.080
hey, guys, we tested this.

00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:38.439
But look at all this other stuff we found.

00:38:38.879 --> 00:38:39.959
There's more experiments.

00:38:39.959 --> 00:38:42.879
Let's go after this. Let's get them excited about it.

00:38:42.879 --> 00:38:49.360
We hype it up. And some of it's like it's not necessarily world changing right from the

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:53.080
get go. But again, kind of the teaching and communicating piece we were talking about

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:57.840
before, we've got to sell them on like, hey, here's this is just step one.

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:00.760
This is just version one. If we keep developing this, think about what we could do.

00:39:01.399 --> 00:39:03.159
I love that, that messaging.

00:39:04.600 --> 00:39:09.280
That's great. Caitlin, I see you had a question here in the chat.

00:39:09.719 --> 00:39:12.919
I was thinking it might be helpful for you to introduce yourself as well.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:15.719
Yeah. Hi. So I'm Caitlin.

00:39:15.719 --> 00:39:18.280
I'm a customer success here, rep here at Fawcett.

00:39:18.280 --> 00:39:21.159
And I work with public sector customers mainly.

00:39:21.600 --> 00:39:28.280
So I've done a lot of work with Army different, mainly SOCOM, Special Forces Operations

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:31.320
Command. So that's a little bit about me.

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:38.919
But my question was, so are there instances of not having enough data, soldier data

00:39:38.919 --> 00:39:45.320
that, you know, that is and how currently is HRC collecting that data?

00:39:46.199 --> 00:39:48.120
So I'm sorry, go ahead.

00:39:48.159 --> 00:39:53.320
Yeah, I want to add in just to continue on, like how how does your team handle when there's

00:39:53.320 --> 00:39:54.280
not enough data?

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:58.360
So we have a ton of data doesn't necessarily mean it's the right data.

00:39:59.479 --> 00:40:02.280
And as we're going through these models, that's that was actually what kicked off our

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:07.120
assessment program. It's like I don't have enough in people's files to be able to say

00:40:07.120 --> 00:40:09.280
what their what their talent attributes are.

00:40:09.679 --> 00:40:14.760
And so we go over to our research entities, Army Research Institute, Army Research Labs

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:19.159
and say, you guys got any kind of existing studies that we can peel a couple things off

00:40:19.159 --> 00:40:24.439
of and take a look at and maybe experiment and go collect some more data with you guys

00:40:24.439 --> 00:40:26.639
on this? We've had a really good partnership with them on it.

00:40:27.239 --> 00:40:31.800
It's also allowed them to kind of modernize how they're approaching research because

00:40:32.239 --> 00:40:35.719
they've got these things that they can peel off and show quick wins from their findings

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:39.439
rather than it's like this five year study that all the leadership is going to change

00:40:39.439 --> 00:40:40.439
out before it's done.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:45.479
And leadership generally, you know, they generally kind of treat that with distrust.

00:40:45.959 --> 00:40:49.280
Chris, I saw something you had posted on LinkedIn.

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:54.399
I think it was maybe like a few days ago about like the importance of being able to take

00:40:54.399 --> 00:40:58.320
time off and to be fully off during that time.

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:03.840
And I saw you were asking some advice to other people from your LinkedIn network, too,

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:09.159
and was just wondering like what your thoughts are on that and what you're you're

00:41:09.199 --> 00:41:11.639
learning from your own network, too.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.239
Well, that's kind of the fun part about this network.

00:41:14.239 --> 00:41:16.959
I love throwing questions out there and just saying, hey, guys, I'm human.

00:41:16.959 --> 00:41:18.840
I don't I do a lot of things right.

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:22.760
I've been put in a position because, you know, you can wave your awesome flag all day.

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:25.399
But it's also like I screw up a lot of things.

00:41:25.399 --> 00:41:26.919
I am horrible at taking time off.

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:31.000
You know, I am I will compulsively go and check things.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:34.719
If not, you know, I've got my Mike Carroll, who's our lead for procurement, but he's also

00:41:34.719 --> 00:41:36.120
my accountability buddy there.

00:41:36.120 --> 00:41:37.879
He's just like, I see you. I see you on teams.

00:41:37.879 --> 00:41:38.879
Get off. Go home.

00:41:39.399 --> 00:41:44.919
Um, so I love throwing things like that out to the community and just saying, hey, you

00:41:44.919 --> 00:41:46.719
know, I'm not the only person who's dealing with this.

00:41:47.239 --> 00:41:51.360
And this is a professional wellness thing that I think all of us can benefit from the

00:41:51.360 --> 00:41:53.520
discussion on. Let me throw it out there.

00:41:53.520 --> 00:41:54.679
You guys tell me what works for you.

00:41:54.679 --> 00:41:56.719
And a lot of it kind of came back that same thing.

00:41:56.719 --> 00:42:02.320
It's like we need that time to do an active or inactive recharge.

00:42:02.679 --> 00:42:07.560
Sometimes it's like doing yoga or cross training when you've been trying to ramp up for

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:11.000
a race. You know, you've got to do something, but make it something that's not work.

00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:15.120
So, you know, trying to figure out those good substitutions or those complimentary

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:18.520
activities. And we talked earlier about, you know, was one of my favorite things to do.

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:21.879
Not at work. I love hiking, love cooking, love going to the beach.

00:42:22.239 --> 00:42:26.479
And I think we've got to let ourselves know that not only is it OK to have hobbies, not

00:42:26.479 --> 00:42:30.879
everything has to be work and hustle, but those things actually complement your ability

00:42:30.879 --> 00:42:32.919
to refresh, recharge and do your job.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:38.439
So I think it's hugely important and always trying to figure out ways to get better at it.

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:43.600
I love that idea of having an accountability buddy, too.

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:49.919
And like when we see our our friends at work are on Slack or on Teams or whatever, when

00:42:49.919 --> 00:42:53.320
they're supposed to be off just saying, hey, what are you doing here?

00:42:53.320 --> 00:42:54.399
Go message me.

00:42:55.800 --> 00:43:00.439
Yeah, my boss is really good at that general joke.

00:43:00.439 --> 00:43:02.399
You'll see me on Teams. He goes, why are you on Teams?

00:43:02.399 --> 00:43:03.399
Go be with your family. Go away.

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:08.800
And so conversely, I'm just like, you better be TEY, boss, because otherwise, why are you

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:09.439
calling me?

00:43:10.199 --> 00:43:15.399
Right. Mike, I see you had a question in the chat a bit earlier.

00:43:15.399 --> 00:43:16.159
Want to jump in here?

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:21.800
No, not really, because now my focus is on this pay time off question.

00:43:23.239 --> 00:43:25.199
I think we should carry on with that thread.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:31.320
Well, OK. Anybody else have thoughts to share on that?

00:43:31.520 --> 00:43:34.760
I see a lot popping up in the chat and resources.

00:43:34.919 --> 00:43:38.879
Yeah. OK, so so since you called me out, Rachel, I'll jump.

00:43:39.159 --> 00:43:47.199
So this is a personal experience and I agree wholeheartedly that time off should be time

00:43:47.199 --> 00:43:55.520
away from work. But the kind of personal anecdote is how many times do I see a quick

00:43:55.520 --> 00:44:00.399
question? Hey, I've got a quick question on Teams and I'm like, oh, yeah, I can answer

00:44:00.399 --> 00:44:02.199
that. And it'll only take a couple of minutes.

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:05.879
And I'll just help this because that will unblock that person.

00:44:06.479 --> 00:44:09.560
Right. So you just fire off a quick, oh, this is where you find that thing.

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:16.959
Right. But the other thing is that if you don't do that, they don't sit there blocked for

00:44:16.959 --> 00:44:21.719
the 24, 48, 72 week long that you're at the office.

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:24.120
They find the solution themselves.

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:29.120
You know, so it's almost like, well, yes, I've been very helpful and have answered this

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:35.360
question quickly, but actually I've taken my brain from doing the thing that I was doing

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:40.600
to answering a work question and then I've got to come back to the kind of out of office

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:42.639
brain. It's hard.

